s''': 85,941\n*'''Approximate number of tests from MDH Public Health Lab''': 13,241\n*'''Approximate number of tests from other labs''': 72,700\n*'''Total positive cases''': 7,234 (+571)\n*'''Deaths''': 428 (+9)\n*'''Cases no longer requiring isolation''': 4,212 (+1,197)\n*'''Total cases requiring hospitalization''': 1,271\n*'''Current hospitalizations''': 396\n*'''Current ICU hospitalizations''': 166\n}}\n\n==Responses==\n===State government===\n[[File: Lake Area Quick Lube sign in White Bear Lake, Minnesota.jpg|thumb|\"Corona Hours\" sign at the Lake Area Quick Lube in White Bear Lake, Minnesota- Auto Repair and Maintenance shops are considered \"essential businesses\"]]\nOn March 10, Minnesota Governor Tim Walz signed a bill to dedicate $20.8 million to state coronavirus response.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOn March 13, Governor Walz declared a peacetime state of emergency.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn March 15, Governor Walz authorized the temporary closing of all public K-12 schools from March 18 until at least March 27.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> On March 25, this closure was extended to May 4.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nOn March 16, the Minnesota legislature began scaling back operations and meeting on an on-call basis.<ref name=\":5\" /> Governor Walz also ordered the closure of public places, including all: restaurants, bars, coffee shops, gyms, theaters, breweries, ski resorts, and other public places until at least March 27. Bars and restaurants in the state were closed only to dine-in customers; the businesses were allowed to continue to serve customers by take-out or delivery orders.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mprnews.org/story/2020/03/16/walz-covid19-bar-restaurant-closure-and-unemployment-help |title=Walz temporarily closes bars, restaurants and gyms to curb COVID-19 spread |last=MPR Staff |website=Minnesota Public Radio |access-date=17 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317231710/https://www.mprnews.org/story/2020/03/16/walz-covid19-bar-restaurant-closure-and-unemployment-help |archive-date=March 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 25, this order was extended until May 1.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nOn March 25, Governor Walz issued a [[stay-at-home order]], claiming that at this point it was too late to \"flatten the curve\" with relation to new cases. The stay-at-home order required Minnesotans to restrict activity outside the home from 11:59&nbsp;p.m. on March 27 until 5 p.m. on April 10.<ref>{{cite news\n| date = March 25, 2020\n| title = Minnesota Press Conference: COVID-19 Stay at Home Order\n| url = https://www.wdio.com/duluth-minnesota-news/minnesota-governor-walz-conference-stay-at-home-order/5684276/\n| accessdate = March 25, 2020\n}}</ref> While the order did continue the closure of bars, restaurants, movie theaters, hair salons, and other \"non-essential\" locations, the majority of workplaces still remained open for some employees in order to provide \"essential services.\" Some of the places deemed \"essential\" included mechanics (bike and auto), chiropractors, grocery stores, any store that sold food or drink including bakeries, butcher shops, liquor stores, and even popcorn shops. Many restaurants continued to stay open for take-out and curbside pickup. Many retail stores also maintained a skeleton staff and offered curbside pickup, or only allowed a few people in the store at one time.<ref>{{cite web |title=Minnesota Critical Businesses List |url=https://mn.gov/deed/assets/naics-critical-list_tcm1045-424829.pdf |website=Minnesota Department of Employment and Economic Development |publisher=Government of Minnesota |accessdate=30 March 2020 |date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Orenstein |first1=Walker |title=Who and what is and isn't covered by Minnesota's new 'Stay-at-Home' order |url=https://www.minnpost.com/state-government/2020/03/who-and-what-is-and-isnt-covered-by-minnesotas-new-stay-at-home-order/ |accessdate=30 March 2020 |publisher=Minnpost.com |date=25 March 2020 |location=Minneapolis, Minnesota}}</ref>\n\n===City governments===\nOn March 14, [[St. Paul, MN|St. Paul]] Mayor [[Melvin Carter (politician)|Melvin Carter]] declared a State of Local Emergency. The city will no longer be issuing any new permits for gatherings of 50 or more people. He also requested that [[Ramsey County, MN|Ramsey County]] police suspend all evictions. The [[St. Paul Public Library]], St. Paul Schools, and all parks and recreation centers including the [[Como Zoo]] were also closed from March 16 through March 27.<ref name=\" schools\" />\n\nIn March, the City of [[Red Wing, Minnesota]] suspended city facilities and shut down the city library due to concerns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://red-wing.org/975/Coronavirus-COVID-19|title=COV-19|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> in March 31, Red Wing reported its first cases at a corrections facility<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.postbulletin.com/life/health/first-covid-19-cases-reported-minnesota-correctional-facilities-including-red-wing/article_9c4af926-7353-11ea-bba3-fbcabfed2e7a.html|title=First COVID-19 cases reported Minnesota correctional facilities, including Red Wing|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Impact on sports==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\nMost of the state's sports teams were affected. Several leagues began postponing or suspending their seasons starting March 12. [[Major League Baseball]] cancelled the remainder of [[spring training]] on that date, and on March 16, they announced that the season will be postponed indefinitely, after the recommendations from the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] to restrict events of more than 50 people for the next eight weeks, affecting the [[2020 Minnesota Twins season|Minnesota Twins]].<ref name=\"mlb\">{{cite web |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/opening-of-regular-season-to-be-pushed-back |title=Opening of regular season to be pushed back |first=Mark |last=Feinsand |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=March 16, 2020 |access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> Also on March 12, the [[National Basketball Association]] announced the season would be suspended for 30 days, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Minnesota Timberwolves season|Minnesota Timberwolves]].<ref name=nba>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games |title=Silver: NBA hiatus likely to last 'at least' 30 days |date=March 12, 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>  In the [[National Hockey League]], the season was suspended for an indefinite amount of time, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Minnesota Wild season|Minnesota Wild]].<ref name=nhl>[https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 NHL statement on coronavirus] NHL, March 12, 2020</ref>\n\nIn college sports, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] canceled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities statewide.<ref name=ncaa>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> The 2020 [[NCAA Division I Wrestling Championships]] were scheduled for March 19\u201321 at [[Minneapolis|Minneapolis']] [[U.S. Bank Stadium]]. By March 11, the NCAA had announced the championship would continue, but none of the anticipated 100,000 fans would be allowed to attend.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shipley |first1=John |title=NCAA decision means empty U.S. Bank Stadium for wrestling championship |url=https://www.twincities.com/2020/03/11/ncaa-decision-means-u-s-bank-stadium-will-be-empty-for-wrestling-championships/ |accessdate=18 March 2020 |publisher=St. Paul Pioneer Press |date=11 March 2020 |location=St. Paul, Minnesota}}</ref> The following day the NCAA canceled all spring championships.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nOn March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>[https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak] MLive.com, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\nOn March 21, the [[Brainerd, Minnesota|Brainerd]] [[Jaycees]] announced the cancelation of the [[Run for the Lakes Marathon]] and all other races taking place over the marathon weekend, which was scheduled for April 24\u201325. The [[COVID-19 pandemic]] ended the 11-year streak of consecutive marathon runnings.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bieser |first1=Toni |title=Brainerd Jaycees Run the Lakes Press Release |url=https://scontent-msp1-1.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t1.0-9/90414801_2772600102787521_4170424978266652672_n.jpg?_nc_cat=107&_nc_sid=110474&_nc_oc=AQkQLcDykFyXA__1XHnQefsaEMA6j_WgN0VuN1eQGAby5JFPCtLBT2gveOCCN-O7jP4&_nc_ht=scontent-msp1-1.xx&oh=6ff9b8f13d6c0ada3a7f4ae9797ea08e&oe=5EA19C8A |website=Facebook.com |publisher=Brainerd Jaycees |accessdate=25 March 2020 |format=PDF}}</ref>\n\n[[Grandma's Marathon]] was held annually for 43 years, making it one of the oldest continually-run marathons in the country. But on March 31, the staff announced that the June 16, 2020, race was canceled due to concerns of spreading [[SARS-CoV-2]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Galioto |first1=Katie |title=Grandma's Marathon canceled due to COVID-19 |url=https://www.startribune.com/grandma-s-marathon-canceled-due-to-covid-19/569250322/ |accessdate=31 March 2020 |publisher=Star Tribune |date=31 March 2020 |location=Minneapolis, Minnesota}}</ref>\n\nOn April 2, race officials decided to cancel the [[Lake Wobegon Trail Marathon]] for the first time since the race began in 2008. The race runs on the state trail from [[Holdingford, Minnesota]], to [[St. Joseph, Minnesota]].\n<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mozey |first1=Brian |title=Lake Wobegon Trail Marathon cancelled due to COVID-19; replaced by virtual race |url=https://www.sctimes.com/story/sports/2020/04/02/lake-wobegon-trail-marathon-cancelled-due-covid-19-virtual-race/5118285002/ |accessdate=4 April 2020 |agency=USA Today |publisher=St. Cloud Times |date=2 April 2020 |location=St. Cloud, Minnesota}}</ref>\n\nBy April 6, nearly 1,000 people in the state had contracted [[COVID-19]], and the [[Rochester, Minnesota]]-based [[Med City Marathon]] race organizers decided to postpone their race weekend from May 23\u201324 to September 4\u20135.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jahns |first1=Isaac |title=Med City Marathon moved to September |url=https://www.medcitybeat.com/news-blog/2020/med-city-marathon-moved-to-september |accessdate=6 April 2020 |publisher=MedCity Beat |date=6 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Bongers |first1=Mark |title=2020 Final Stretch Events \u2013 Med City Marathon presented by Active PT |url=https://www.medcitymarathon.com/images/Med_City_date_rescheduled.pdf |website=Medcitymarathon.com |accessdate=6 April 2020 |location=Rochester, Minnesota |date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Additional Diagrams and Images==\n<gallery>\nfile:COVID-19 Case Status in Minnesota.svg|Status of cases beginning 14 April 2020\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|COVID-19 pandemic in Minnesota}}\n* [https://www.health.state.mn.us/diseases/coronavirus/index.html Coronavirus information] from the [[Minnesota Department of Health]]\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Medicine|Viruses|Coronavirus disease 2019}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|Minnesota]]\n[[Category:2020 in Minnesota|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Health in Minnesota]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in Minnesota, United States}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Minnesota\n| map2            = File:COVID-19 Cases in Minnesota by counties.svg\n| legend2         = Number of cases per Minnesota county ''(enlarge image for legend)''\n| map3            = COVID-19 deaths in Minnesota by counties.svg\n| legend3         = Number of deaths per Minnesota county ''(enlarge image for legend)''\n| map1            = {{multiple image|border=infobox|perrow=1/2/2|total_width=250\n| image1 = Minneapolis (49674291772).jpg\n| image2 = Faith & Hope are not cancelled; a sign outside St. Mary's Cathedral in St Cloud, Minnesota.jpg\n| image3 = In The Heart Of The Beast Theatre in Minneapolis, Minnesota.jpg\n| image4 = A worker cleans the Mary Tyler Moore statue as a man walks by in a medical face mask in Minneapolis, Minnesota.jpg\n| footer_align = center\n| footer = (clockwise from top){{flatlist|\n*[[Minnesota State Highway 65]] leading into downtown [[Minneapolis]], devoid of traffic\n*In The Heart Of The Beast Theatre in Minneapolis\n*Worker disinfecting the [[Mary Tyler Moore|Mary Tyler Moore statue]] on [[Nicollet Mall]]\n*St. Mary's Cathedral in [[St. Cloud, Minnesota|St. Cloud]]\n}}\n}}\n| disease         = [[Covid-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Minnesota]]\n| first_case      = [[Saint Paul, Minnesota|St. Paul]]\n| arrival_date    = March 6, 2020\n| origin          = ''Grand Princess''\n| confirmed_cases = 6,663\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = \n| hospitalized_cases = 912 (cumulative) <br/> 389 (current)\n| critical_cases  = 324 (cumulative) <br/> 135 (current)\n| recovery_cases  = 2,397\n| deaths          = 419\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = [https://www.health.state.mn.us/diseases/coronavirus/situation.html Minnesota Department of Health]\n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 pandemic]] in Minnesota is part of an ongoing pandemic of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) caused by the virus [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]] in the [[US state]] of [[Minnesota]]. The first confirmed case was reported on March 1, 2020. Governor [[Tim Walz]] declared a [[state of emergency]] on March 13.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=http://www.startribune.com/minnesota-declares-peacetime-emergency-to-combat-coronavirus-as-cases-rise-to-14/568772352/|title=Minnesota declares peacetime emergency to combat coronavirus as cases rise to 14|work=Star Tribune|access-date=2020-03-15|date=2020-03-14|last1=Howatt|first1=Glenn}}</ref> Attempts to [[flatten the curve|mitigate the virus' spread]] have led to severe socioeconomic disruptions in the state, as well as the temporary closure of most schools, religious institutions, and sporting centers.\n\n==Timeline==\n{{stack|clear=right|{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Minnesota medical cases chart}}}}\n{{stack|clear=right|{{2020 coronavirus pandemic data/Minnesota medical cases by county}}}}\n\n=== January\u2013February ===\nThe [[Minnesota Department of Health]] began testing for the virus on January 20. During this time, no cases were positively tested in Minnesota. State health officials were monitoring for potential cases and making plans to contain future [[outbreak]]s.<ref name=\"90 tests\">{{cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/mayo-finds-no-coronavirus-in-first-90-tests/568776382/?refresh=true|title=Mayo finds no coronavirus in first 90 tests|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mprnews.org/story/2020/01/24/two-coronavirus-cases-suspected-in-minnesota-officials-prep-for-spread|title=2 coronavirus cases suspected in Minnesota; officials prep for spread|website=MPR News|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\n[[Mayo Clinic]] in [[Rochester, MN|Rochester]] began fast-tracking development of a test for the virus in mid-February.<ref name=\"90 tests\" />\n\n=== March ===\n\n==== March 6 ====\nThe first positive test is confirmed in the state. The patient had recently taken a [[Grand Princess]] cruise and had been on a ship with a known case. The patient was an older adult from [[Ramsey County, MN|Ramsey County]] and had started having symptoms on February 25 and received medical care on March 5. They returned home to recover in [[Isolation (health care)|isolation]]. At this time, Governor [[Tim Walz]] said \"I'm confident that Minnesota is prepared for this.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kare11.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/coronavirus-in-minnesota/89-da7d7967-ff29-4d69-ae12-079d12fa5752|title=Health Department confirms first 'presumptive' coronavirus case in Minnesota|website=kare11.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\n==== March 8 ====\nThe second positive test in the state is confirmed in [[Carver County]]. A patient in their 50s began having symptoms on March 2 after likely being exposed while traveling in [[Europe]] in February. They sought medical care on March 7 and begin recovering at home in isolation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kare11.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/health-officials-confirm-second-presumptive-case-of-coronavirus-in-minnesota/89-738dd473-7ded-47a5-8623-daa36ff9d2f3|title=Health officials confirm second presumptive case of coronavirus in Minnesota|website=kare11.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\n==== March 10 ====\nThe third Minnesota patient is hospitalized in critical condition at an [[Anoka County]] hospital. The patient is in their 30s and had no obvious underlying conditions. They had developed symptoms on February 28 after being in contact with international travelers which likely exposed them to the [[virus]]. They were evaluated on March 3 and released at that time without being tested, which the [[Minnesota Department of Health]] had deemed \"appropriate\". They returned for medical services on March 9.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kare11.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/minnesota-third-coronavirus-case/89-152af222-6c7b-4991-8c86-d389c80226c4|title=MDH: Anoka County coronavirus patient is in critical condition|website=kare11.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> According to health officials there was no evidence the virus was being transmitted person to person in the state yet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/minnesota-confirms-third-covid-19-case-patient-is-hospitalized-in-critical-condition/568672732/|title=Minnesota confirms third coronavirus case; patient is hospitalized in critical condition|website=Star Tribune|access-date=March 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311144250/http://www.startribune.com/minnesota-confirms-third-covid-19-case-patient-is-hospitalized-in-critical-condition/568672732/|archive-date=March 11, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA bill to set aside $20.8 million for Minnesota's coronavirus outbreak response is signed by Governor Walz. This money is in addition to the $4.6 million already in the account for [[public health]] response, totaling over $25 million.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kare11.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/gov-walz-signs-21-million-coronavirus-funding-bill/89-227ff3a2-159a-44ea-8be1-21ec0d841062|title=Gov. Walz signs $21 million coronavirus funding bill|website=kare11.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\n==== March 11 ====\nFive total cases in Minnesota have been confirmed. The fourth patient is in their 50s, in [[Olmsted County, Minnesota|Olmsted County]], and was diagnosed at the [[Mayo Clinic]] in [[Rochester, MN|Rochester]]. The fifth patient is in Ramsey County and in their 30s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mprnews.org/story/2020/03/11/olmsted-county-says-it-has-minnesotas-4th-covid19-case|title=Minnesota's 4th, 5th COVID-19 cases surface in Olmsted, Ramsey counties|website=MPR News|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nThe [[University of Minnesota]] announces the suspension of classes across all five campuses. The University will extend its spring break to two weeks, ending March 18, at which time classes will resume through online instruction. Online instruction will continue until at least April 1 including field experience and clinical. During this time, residence halls, dining services, and other student services will continue normal operation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mprnews.org/story/2020/03/11/u-of-m-suspends-campus-classes-moving-instruction-online-over-covid19-fears|title=U of M suspends campus classes, moving instruction online over COVID-19 fears|website=MPR News|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\n[[Mayo Clinic]] also began \"drive-through testing\" for the virus, though patients still needed to be approved to be tested by telephone screening.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.postbulletin.com/life/health/mayo-clinic-starts-drive-thru-testing-for-covid/article_0087a856-63e3-11ea-be76-c7558f932526.html|title=Mayo Clinic starts drive-thru testing for COVID-19|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== March 12 ====\nNine total cases are confirmed in Minnesota with the four new cases all considered to be travel-related. The new cases are reported in [[Hennepin County, Minnesota|Hennepin]], [[Dakota County, Minnesota|Dakota]], and [[Stearns County, Minnesota|Stearns]] counties. All non-critical cases had begun recovering at home in isolation.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mprnews.org/story/2020/03/12/9-minnesota-covid19-cases-now-in-7-counties|title=MN health: 9 COVID-19 cases now; no plans to close schools|website=MPR News|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> At this time, the [[Minnesota Department of Health]] did not recommend closing schools.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==== March 13 ====\n14 total cases confirmed in Minnesota; the new cases are reported to be in Hennepin, Ramsey, Anoka, Dakota, Carver, and [[Wright County, Minnesota|Wright]] counties. As of this date, more than 550 people have been tested for the virus in the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://minnesota.cbslocal.com/2020/03/13/coronavirus-in-minnesota-number-of-positive-cases-climbs-to-14/|title=Coronavirus In Minnesota: Number Of Positive COVID-19 Cases Climbs To 14|date=2020-03-13|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nGovernor Walz declares a peacetime [[state of emergency]]. He says, \"We are going into a heightened state of readiness to protect Minnesotans.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==== March 14 ====\n21 total cases confirmed in Minnesota. Three people in Hennepin county tested positive, two of the patients are in their 60s and one in their 30s. A patient in their 30s is confirmed in Ramsey county. One patient in their 60s in Stearns, another in their 60s in Renville, and a teenager in Dakota county are also confirmed. All cases are connected to contact with a confirmed case of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]. All seven patients begin recovering at home in self-isolation. 868 total tests have been conducted.<ref name=\"grows to 21\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mprnews.org/story/2020/03/14/number-of-covid19-cases-in-minnesota-grows-to-21|title=Number of COVID-19 cases in Minnesota grows to 21|website=MPR News|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\n==== March 15 ====\n35 total cases confirmed in Minnesota. The ages of the new patients range from 20 to 94 and are reported to be from Hennepin, Ramsey, Dakota, Olmsted, [[Waseca County, Minnesota|Waseca]], and [[Washington County, Minnesota|Washington]] counties. Additionally, the Minnesota Department of Health reports  three of the new cases were exposed via [[Transmission (medicine)|community transmission]].<ref name=\"grows to 21\" />\n\nGovernor Tim Walz announces the temporary closure of all Minnesota K-12 public schools from March 18 until March 27. He says, \"My top priority as Governor is the safety of Minnesotans. As a former teacher, and father of two teenage kids, I'm especially focused on the safety of our children.\"<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kare11.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/mn-schools-close-coronavirus/89-ebd39743-f5fb-4378-98e7-7ce30805867e|title=Minnesota schools to close for coronavirus|website=kare11.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|title=Watch live: Minnesota governor updates on coronavirus response|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ki-jSIVMYBE|language=en|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> During the school shutdown, meals and mental health services will still be provided to students in need.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/minnesota-schools-will-close-for-eight-days-due-to-coronavirus-pandemic/568812082/?refresh=true|title=Minnesota Gov. Tim Walz closing K-12 schools as COVID-19 spreads|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref> Under the governor's order, schools will remain open for elementary-aged children of health care workers and other emergency workers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fox9.com/news/walz-schools-to-remain-open-for-children-of-health-care-workers-emergency-responders|title=Walz: Schools to remain open for children of health care workers, emergency responders|date=March 15, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref> Teachers will be using this time to plan for a possibility of weeks of long-distance learning.<ref name=\"schools\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mprnews.org/story/2020/03/14/walz-minnesota-schools-closed-covid19|title=Walz announces temporary closure of Minnesota K-12 public schools|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====March 16====\nAn additional 19 positive cases are confirmed in the state, bringing the total number of cases to 54. More than 1893 patients have been tested, with several clinics, including [[M Health Fairview]] and Mayo Clinic only reporting the number of patients who test positive and not the total amount tested.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bringmethenews.com/minnesota-news/minnesotas-confirmed-coronavirus-cases-rise-to-54|title=Minnesota's confirmed coronavirus cases rise to 54|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Minnesota Legislature]] begins scaling back operations as the [[Minnesota House of Representatives|State House]] and [[Minnesota Senate|Senate]] will be meeting on an on-call basis. For future meetings, they will be meeting in locations that allow for 6 feet between representatives.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=https://minnesota.cbslocal.com/2020/03/16/coronavirus-in-minnesota-legislature-scales-back-amid-spread-of-covid-19/|title=Coronavirus In Minnesota: Legislature Scales Back Amid Spread Of COVID-19|date=2020-03-16|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nGovernor Tim Walz announces in Executive Order 20-04 that all non-essential businesses close until March 27, 2020, citing the first confirmed case of community spread, detected the previous day, as his cause for this action.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mn.gov/governor/assets/2020_03_16_EO_20_04_Bars_Restaurants_tcm1055-423380.pdf|title=Emergency Executive Order 20-04}}</ref>\n\n====March 17====\nSix more cases are reported, bringing the total number of cases to 60.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inforum.com/lifestyle/health/5002621-6-new-coronavirus-cases-in-MN-total-now-60|title=6 new coronavirus cases in MN, total now 60|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Minnesota Department of Health (MDH) today announces that due to a national shortage of COVID-19 laboratory testing materials, the state is forced to [https://www.health.state.mn.us/news/pressrel/2020/covid031720.html make adjustments to its testing criteria] to focus on the highest priority specimens, including hospitalized patients.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.health.state.mn.us/news/pressrel/2020/covid031720.html|title=News release: MDH issues updated guidance on COVID-19 testing criteria|website=www.health.state.mn.us|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n==== March 18 ====\n[[File:Minnesota National Guard (49673449643).jpg|thumb|Delivering [[surgical mask]]s in Minnesota]]\n[[Rochester Public Library (Minnesota)]] closed for the public<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rplmn.org/my-rpl/about-us/coronavirus-faq|title=CORONAVIRUS & THE LIBRARY {{!}} Rochester (MN) Public Library|website=www.rplmn.org|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\nSeventeen more cases are reported, bringing the total number of cases to 77.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n==== March 19 ====\nTwelve additional cases are reported, bringing the total number of cases to 89.\n\n==== March 20 ====\n26 additional cases are reported, bringing the total number of cases to 115 and number of affected counties to 21.<ref name=\"MN Official\">{{cite web|url=https://www.health.state.mn.us/diseases/coronavirus/situation.html|title=Situation Update for Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) - Minnesota Department of Health|website=www.health.state.mn.us|access-date=2020-05-04}}</ref>\n\n==== March 21 ====\nThe state confirms its first death due to the virus; the patient was from Ramsey County and was in their 80's. The patient had contracted the virus from a confirmed case.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.health.state.mn.us/news/pressrel/2020/covid032120.html|title=Health officials confirm first death due to COVID-19 in Minnesota|accessdate= March 24, 2020}}</ref> Lieutenant Governor [[Peggy Flanagan]] also confirms her brother died due to the coronavirus in [[Nashville, TN]]. He was [[Tennessee]]'s second confirmed death due to the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wbir.com/article/news/local/tns-second-covid-19-death-was-brother-of-mn-lieutenant-governor/51-73f4f609-68a7-4a49-91b9-e11553ebdc55|title= TN's second COVID-19 death was brother of MN lieutenant governor|accessdate= March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== March 23 ====\n[[File:A comedy theater marquee referencing coronavirus in Minneapolis, Minnesota.jpg|thumb|A comedy theater marquee referencing coronavirus in Minneapolis, Minnesota]]\nThe governor makes several announcements regarding the state's response to the virus:{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n*A small business loan program would be made available for possibly 5000 businesses during the week for amounts between $2,500 and $35,000\n*All elective veterinary surgeries would be halted\n*The budget for the response to the virus would be revised, asking for an additional $365 million\n\nThe state has 235 positive total confirmed cases of the virus and 1 death.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.mprnews.org/story/2020/03/24/latest-on-covid19-in-minnesota|title= Latest on COVID-19 in Minnesota: Cases rise to 262; 15 currently hospitalized|accessdate= March 24, 2020}}</ref> The governor makes the announcement from quarantine; a member of his security staff tested positive for the virus. He said he is not experiencing any symptoms. The husband of Senator [[Amy Klobuchar]] is hospitalized due to the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://wxow.com/2020/03/23/mn-gov-walz-to-self-quarantine-after-having-contact-with-person-who-tested-positive-for-covid-19/|title= UPDATE: Walz self-quarantines; Klobuchar's husband hospitalized|date= March 23, 2020|accessdate= March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== March 24 ====\nThe Minnesota Department of Health announces there are a total of 262 confirmed cases of the virus in the state. Twenty-two of those cases have required hospitalization and there has been 1 confirmed death. At the time, only 15 people are still hospitalized and 88 patients who had tested positive for the virus have recovered and are no longer required to be in isolation.<ref name=\"MN Official\" />\n{{plainlist|\n*'''Approximate number of tests from MDH Public Health Lab''': 5,812\n*'''Total positive cases''': 262\n*'''Deaths''': 1\n*'''Cases no longer requiring isolation''': 88\n*'''Total active cases''': 173\n*'''Total cases requiring hospitalization''': 21\n*'''Current hospitalizations''': 15\n}}\n\n==== March 25 ====\nThe state announces a total of 287 confirmed cases of the virus, 26 of which required hospitalization. It is reported that the actual number of cases was likely at least 10 times higher than this number.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mprnews.org/story/2020/03/25/latest-on-covid19-in-minnesota|title='Buckle it up': Walz orders MN to 'stay at home' to curb virus spread|website=MPR News|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n{{plainlist|\n*'''Total approximate number of completed tests''': 11,475\n*'''Approximate number of tests from MDH Public Health Lab''': 6,365\n*'''Approximate number of tests from other labs''': 5,110\n*'''Total positive cases''': 287\n*'''Deaths''': 1\n*'''Cases no longer requiring isolation''': 122\n*'''Total active cases''': 164\n*'''Total cases requiring hospitalization''': 35\n*'''Current hospitalizations''': 26\n}}\n\nGovernor Tim Walz signs Executive Order 20-20. This order states that all people currently residing in Minnesota are to [[Stay-at-home order|shelter in place]] beginning March 27, 2020 at 11:59PM through April 10, 2020 at 5:00PM.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mn.gov/governor/assets/3a.%20EO%2020-20%20FINAL%20SIGNED%20Filed_tcm1055-425020.pdf|title=Emergency Executive Order 20-20}}</ref> Walz also signs executive orders 20-18 and 20\u201319. Executive order 20-18 extended the previous statewide closure of all non-essential businesses, which was due to end March 27, 2020, to remain closed until May 1, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.leg.state.mn.us/archive/execorders/20-18.pdf|title=Emergency Executive Order 20-18}}</ref> Executive Order 20-19 extended school closures and a \"Distance Learning Period\" was ordered to begin in Minnesota from March 30, 2020 until May 4, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.leg.state.mn.us/archive/execorders/20-19.pdf|title=Emergency Executive Order 20-19}}</ref>\n\n==== March 26 ====\nThe state announces that the total number of confirmed cases has risen to 346, the largest jump since the pandemic reached Minnesota. 31 cases require hospitalization. The Minnesota Department of Health also confirms a second death caused by the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mprnews.org/story/2020/03/26/latest-covid-19-minnesota|title=Live: Walz briefing media on COVID-19 as cases rise, MN sees second death|website=MPR News|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n{{plainlist|\n*'''Total approximate number of completed tests''': 12,950\n*'''Approximate number of tests from MDH Public Health Lab''': 6,849\n*'''Approximate number of tests from other labs''': 6,101\n*'''Total positive cases''': 346\n*'''Deaths''': 2\n*'''Cases no longer requiring isolation''': 134\n*'''Total active cases''': 210\n*'''Total cases requiring hospitalization''': 41\n*'''Current hospitalizations''': 31\n}}\n\n==== March 27 ====\nThe state announces a new total of 398 confirmed cases, with 34 persons in hospital and 14 in ICU at the time. The state also confirms two more deaths as a result of the virus, bringing the total to 4.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://minnesota.cbslocal.com/2020/03/27/coronavirus-in-minnesota-number-of-positive-covid-19-cases-climbs-to-398-death-toll-climbs-to-4/|title=Coronavirus In Minnesota: Number Of Positive COVID-19 Cases Approaches 400, Death Toll Climbs To 4|date=2020-03-27|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> All of the deceased persons to this point are reported to be in their eighties.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n{{plainlist|\n*'''Total approximate number of completed tests''': 14,003\n*'''Approximate number of tests from MDH Public Health Lab''': 6,929\n*'''Approximate number of tests from other labs''': 7,074\n*'''Total positive cases''': 398\n*'''Deaths''': 4\n*'''Cases no longer requiring isolation''': 180\n*'''Total active cases''': 214\n*'''Total cases requiring hospitalization''': 51\n*'''Current hospitalizations''': 34\n}}\n\n==== March 28 ====\nIn the first day of Gov. Tim Walz's \"Stay at Home\" executive order, the state reports a new total of 441 confirmed cases, with 30 persons reported to be hospitalized at the time. A fifth death resulting from the virus is confirmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://minnesota.cbslocal.com/2020/03/28/coronavirus-in-minnesota-positive-covid-19-case-total-rises-to-441-death-toll-reaches-5/|title=Coronavirus In Minnesota: Positive COVID-19 Case Total Rises To 441, Death Toll Reaches 5|date=2020-03-28|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n{{plainlist|\n*'''Total approximate number of completed tests''': 16,129\n*'''Approximate number of tests from MDH Public Health Lab''': 7,290\n*'''Approximate number of tests from other labs''': 8,839\n*'''Total positive cases''': 441\n*'''Deaths''': 5\n*'''Cases no longer requiring isolation''': 220\n*'''Total active cases''': 216\n*'''Total cases requiring hospitalization''': 57\n*'''Current hospitalizations''': 30\n}}\n\n==== March 29 ====\nSixty-two new cases are reported, bringing the total number of cases to 503. A total of 75 cases required hospitalization, with 39 cases currently being hospitalized. The state also reports 4 new deaths, bringing the total to 9.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://minnesota.cbslocal.com/2020/03/29/coronavirus-in-minnesota-number-of-positive-covid-19-cases-increase-to-503/|title=Coronavirus In Minnesota: Number Of Positive COVID-19 Cases Increase To 503; 4 More Deaths Reported|date=2020-03-29|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n{{plainlist|\n*'''Total approximate number of completed tests''': 17,657\n*'''Approximate number of tests from MDH Public Health Lab''': 7,703\n*'''Approximate number of tests from other labs''': 9,954\n*'''Total positive cases''': 503\n*'''Deaths''': 9\n*'''Cases no longer requiring isolation''': 252\n*'''Total active cases''': 242\n*'''Total cases requiring hospitalization''': 75\n*'''Current hospitalizations''': 39\n}}\n\n==== March 30 ====\nAn updated total of 576 confirmed cases are reported, 73 more than the previous day; 56 persons are currently hospitalized and 24 in ICU. One more death is  reported, bringing the total to 10. The Minnesota Department of Health also reports there are 260 patients no longer requiring isolation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://minnesota.cbslocal.com/2020/03/30/coronavirus-in-minnesota-number-of-positive-covid-19-cases-rises-to-576-10th-death-reported/|title=Coronavirus In Minnesota: Number Of Positive COVID-19 Cases Rises To 576; 10th Death Reported|date=2020-03-30|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n{{plainlist|\n*'''Total approximate number of completed tests''': 18,822\n*'''Approximate number of tests from MDH Public Health Lab''': 7,948\n*'''Approximate number of tests from other labs''': 10,874\n*'''Total positive cases''': 576\n*'''Deaths''': 10\n*'''Cases no longer requiring isolation''': 260\n*'''Total active cases''': 297\n*'''Total cases requiring hospitalization''': 92\n*'''Current hospitalizations''': 56\n*'''Current ICU hospitalizations''': 24\n}}\n\n==== March 31 ====\nThe Minnesota Department of Health daily update for March 31 reflected the following numbers:<ref name=\"MN Official\" />\n{{plainlist|\n*'''Total approximate number of completed tests''': 19,780\n*'''Approximate number of tests from MDH Public Health Lab''': 8,104\n*'''Approximate number of tests from other labs''': 11,676\n*'''Total positive cases''': 629\n*'''Deaths''': 12\n*'''Cases no longer requiring isolation''': 288\n*'''Total active cases''': 329\n*'''Total cases requiring hospitalization''': 112\n*'''Current hospitalizations''': 56\n*'''Current ICU hospitalizations''': 26\n}}\n\n=== April ===\n\n==== April 1 ====\nAt the beginning of the new month, the Minnesota Department of health reported 689 confirmed cases, with 54 persons hospitalized and 27 in ICU. The death toll climbed to 17 and 342 cases no longer required isolation.<ref name=\"MN Official\" /> Long-term care residents account for 11 of the 17 deaths, and account for 38 confirmed cases, with 22 cases among long-term care workers.  42 long-term care facilities have had at least one confirmed case, with one facility accounting for six cases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.startribune.com/minnesota-covid-19-cases-increase-by-60-to-689-with-5-more-deaths/569284402/|title=Minnesota COVID-19 cases increase by 60 to 689 with 5 more deaths|website=www.startribune.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n{{plainlist|\n*'''Total approximate number of completed tests''': 21,191\n*'''Approximate number of tests from MDH Public Health Lab''': 8,280\n*'''Approximate number of tests from other labs''': 12,911\n*'''Total positive cases''': 689\n*'''Deaths''': 17\n*'''Cases no longer requiring isolation''': 342\n*'''Total active cases''': 330\n*'''Total cases requiring hospitalization''': 122\n*'''Current hospitalizations''': 54\n*'''Current ICU hospitalizations''': 27\n}}\n\n==== April 2 ====\nThe Minnesota Department of Health daily update for April 2 reflected the following numbers:<ref name=\"MN Official\" />\n{{plainlist|\n*'''Total approximate number of completed tests''': 22,394\n*'''Approximate number of tests from MDH Public Health Lab''': 8,580\n*'''Approximate number of tests from other labs''': 13,814\n*'''Total positive cases''': 742\n*'''Deaths''': 18\n*'''Cases no longer requiring isolation''': 373\n*'''Total active cases''': 351\n*'''Total cases requiring hospitalization''': 138\n*'''Current hospitalizations''': 75\n*'''Current ICU hospitalizations''': 38\n}}\n\nLong-term care residents accounted for 49 cases (a daily increase of 7) including 11 deaths, with cases among long-term care workers stagnant at 22.  47 long-term care facilities had known cases (a daily increase of five), with one facility accounting for eight cases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.startribune.com/minnesota-covid-19-infections-hit-742-with-53-new-cases-and-1-more-death/569319192/|title=With COVID-19 hospitalizations rising in-state, deal reached on treatment costs|website=www.startribune.com|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==== April 3 ====\nThe Minnesota Department of Health daily update for April 3 reflected the following numbers:<ref name=\"MN Official\" />\n{{plainlist|\n*'''Total approximate number of completed tests''': 24,227\n*'''Approximate number of tests from MDH Public Health Lab''': 8,682\n*'''Approximate number of tests from other labs''': 15,545\n*'''Total positive cases''': 789\n*'''Deaths''': 22\n*'''Cases no longer requiring isolation''': 410\n*'''Total active cases''': 357\n*'''Total cases requiring hospitalization''': 156\n*'''Current hospitalizations''': 86\n*'''Current ICU hospitalizations''': 40\n}}\n\n==== April 4 ====\nThe Minnesota Department of Health daily update for April 4 reflected the following numbers:<ref name=\"MN Official\" />\n{{plainlist|\n*'''Total approximate number of completed tests''': 25,423\n*'''Approximate number of tests from MDH Public Health Lab''': 8,738\n*'''Approximate number of tests from other labs''': 16,685\n*'''Total positive cases''': 865\n*'''Deaths''': 24\n*'''Cases no longer requiring isolation''': 440\n*'''Total active cases''': 401\n*'''Total cases requiring hospitalization''': 180\n*'''Current hospitalizations''': 95\n*'''Current ICU hospitalizations''': 42\n}}\n\n==== April 5 ====\nThe Minnesota Department of Health daily update for April 5 reflected the following numbers:<ref name=\"MN Official\" />\n{{plainlist|\n*'''Total approximate number of completed tests''': 26,777\n*'''Approximate number of tests from MDH Public Health Lab''': 8,846\n*'''Approximate number of tests from other labs''': 17,931\n*'''Total positive cases''': 935\n*'''Deaths''': 29\n*'''Cases no longer requiring isolation''': 451\n*'''Total active cases''': 455\n*'''Total cases requiring hospitalization''': 202\n*'''Current hospitalizations''': 106\n*'''Current ICU hospitalizations''': 48\n}}\n\n==== April 6 ====\nThe Minnesota Department of Health daily update for April 6 reflected the following numbers:<ref name=\"MN Official\" />\n{{plainlist|\n*'''Total approximate number of completed tests''': 28,128\n*'''Approximate number of tests from MDH Public Health Lab''': 8,876\n*'''Approximate number of tests from other labs''': 19,252\n*'''Total positive cases''': 986\n*'''Deaths''': 30\n*'''Cases no longer requiring isolation''': 470\n*'''Total active cases''': 486\n*'''Total cases requiring hospitalization''': 223\n*'''Current hospitalizations''': 115\n*'''Current ICU hospitalizations''': 57\n}}\n\n==== April 7 ====\nThe Minnesota Department of Health daily update for April 7 reflected the following numbers:<ref name=\"MN Official\" />\n{{plainlist|\n*'''Total approximate number of completed tests''': 29,260\n*'''Approximate number of tests from MDH Public Health Lab''': 8,922\n*'''Approximate number of tests from other labs''': 20,338\n*'''Total positive cases''': 1,069\n*'''Deaths''': 34\n*'''Cases no longer requiring isolation''': 549\n*'''Total active cases''': 486\n*'''Total cases requiring hospitalization''': 242\n*'''Current hospitalizations''': 120\n*'''Current ICU hospitalizations''': 64\n}}\n\n==== April 8 ====\nGovernor [[Tim Walz]] extended the Stay at Home (Executive Order 20-33) order until May 3 at 11:59 PM. He cited his reason for doing so due to the new data and new discoveries on about [[COVID-19]] since the original order was put in place. He is also allowing hardware and garden shops to open so long as they follow all the Minnesota Department of Health guidelines.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mn.gov/governor/news/#/detail/appId/1/id/427372 |title=Governor Walz Extends Stay Home Order for Minnesotans |website= Office of Governor Tim Walz and Lt. Governor Peggy Flanagan |date=2020-04-08 |accessdate=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nThe Minnesota Department of Health's situation update 